# Messy Data Cleanup
# AI fixes inconsistent data in a list — normalizing formats, correcting typos, and standardizing entries.

[var: SITE = https://microsoft.sharepoint-df.com/teams/ZachDemos/]
[var: LIST = https://microsoft.sharepoint-df.com/teams/ZachDemos/Lists/Customer%20Directory/]
[category: Lists & Data]

[section: setup]

Verify the "Customer Directory" list exists with 8 rows of intentionally messy
data. Check that the original messy values are present — mixed-case names,
inconsistent phone formats, varied state formats, typos in Status. If clean
data from a previous run is present, re-enter the original messy values using
grid view.

[navigate: ${LIST}]

[open-chat]

[new-chat]

Confirm 8 rows are visible with messy data: "sarah connor" (lowercase),
"555.987.6543" (dot format), "Washington" (full state name), "ative" (typo),
etc.

[pause]

[section: demo]

[navigate: ${LIST}]

This is what happens when 10 different sales reps enter data their own way.
Look at the phone numbers — four different formats. Look at the states —
abbreviations, full names, "Calif." as an informal abbreviation. Industry
has "tech," "Technology," and "retail" all meaning different things. And
there are typos in the Status column — "ative" and "acitve."

[pause]

[open-chat]

[prompt: Clean up this list. Standardize phone numbers to (555) 123-4567 format. Fix contact names to proper capitalization. Normalize State to two-letter abbreviations. Standardize Industry values (for example, 'tech' and 'Technology' should both be 'Technology'). Fix any typos in the Status column.]

[wait]

Look at the transformation. Every phone number is now the same format. Contact
names are properly capitalized. "Calif." became CA. "Washington" became WA.
"tech" and "retail" became "Technology" and "Retail." And the typos — "ative"
and "acitve" — are both fixed to "Active." Point out that it also fixed
"Woodgrove bank" to "Woodgrove Bank" and city capitalization.

[pause]

Now let's see if the clean data reveals anything interesting.

[prompt: Are there any potential duplicate companies or contacts in this list?]

[wait]

No exact duplicates, but Copilot flagged that three companies are in the
Technology industry and noted the concentration. Clean data is queryable data.
Messy data is invisible data.

[pause]

[screenshot: tools/screenshots/10-messy-data-cleanup-final.png]

[section: reset]

Re-enter the original messy data for all 8 rows using grid view. Restore:
lowercase names, mixed phone formats, full state names, industry
inconsistencies, and Status typos.

[navigate: ${LIST}]

[new-chat]
